With a data like: 
```
data = %{
  &quot;Almond Fudge&quot; =&gt; [
    %{date: &quot;2019-01-01&quot;, quantity: 1},
    %{date: &quot;2019-01-02&quot;, quantity: 1},
    %{date: &quot;2019-01-04&quot;, quantity: 3},
    %{date: &quot;2019-01-05&quot;, quantity: 5}
  ],
  &quot;Banana Split&quot; =&gt; [
    %{date: &quot;2019-01-02&quot;, quantity: 3},
    %{date: &quot;2019-01-02&quot;, quantity: 5},
    %{date: &quot;2019-01-02&quot;, quantity: 3},
    %{date: &quot;2019-01-02&quot;, quantity: 5}
  ]
}
```
You could do something like this:

```elixir
Enum.map(data, fn {product, sales} -&gt;              
  {
    product,                          
    Enum.group_by(sales, &amp;(String.slice(&amp;1.date, 0, 7)), &amp;(&amp;1.quantity))
    |&gt; Enum.map(fn {k, v} -&gt;
      {k, Enum.sum(v)}
    end) |&gt; Map.new()
  }
end) |&gt; Map.new()
```

This line: `Enum.group_by(sales, &amp;(&amp;1.date), &amp;(&amp;1.quantity))` will create maps with the dates as keys and a list of values as values.

And then you can convert that to a map with the date as keys and the total sum as values piping it into: `Enum.map(fn {k, v} -&gt; {k, Enum.sum(v)} end) |&gt; Map.new()`

And the final result will be:

```elixir
%{&quot;Almond Fudge&quot; =&gt; %{&quot;2019-01&quot; =&gt; 10}, &quot;Banana Split&quot; =&gt; %{&quot;2019-01&quot; =&gt; 16}}
```

Or, for the exact result you want, if you don&#39;t want the dates as keys, you can replace that line for: `|&gt; Enum.map(fn {k, v} -&gt; %{date: k, quantity: Enum.sum(v)} end)}`

Leaving you with:

```elixir
Enum.map(data, fn {product, sales} -&gt;                                                                          
  {
    product,                                                                                                    
    Enum.group_by(sales, &amp;(String.slice(&amp;1.date, 0, 7)), &amp;(&amp;1.quantity))
    |&gt; Enum.map(fn {k, v} -&gt; %{date: k, quantity: Enum.sum(v)} end)}             
end) |&gt; Map.new() 
```

For a result of:

```elixir
%{
  &quot;Almond Fudge&quot; =&gt; [%{date: &quot;2019-01&quot;, quantity: 10}],
  &quot;Banana Split&quot; =&gt; [%{date: &quot;2019-01&quot;, quantity: 16}]
}
```

Thanks to @zwippie for pointing out to String.slice. I hadn&#39;t realized you were asking for the month. `String.slice/3` will take a string, the initial position, and the length. So Slicing the date string from 0, taking 7 digits would produce strings with the year and month.

